N2  - Background: Age-related cognitive decline has become a major public health concern. As the population ages, the number of older adults experiencing cognitive and functional disturbances from dementia has increased. There is currently a paucity of effective interventions to prevent or treat cognitive decline and prevent dementia in the elderly. While cognitive training (CT) can be effective in these domains, the overall efficacy and transfer of CT has been limited. By pairing tDCS with CT, we have the potential for enhancing the neuroplastic response of brain tissue engaged during CT and enhance training benefits. Methods: The recently NIH-funded “Augmenting Cognitive Training in Older Adults: the ACT study” (Woods, PI) is the largest NIH-funded phase III tDCS clinical trial to date and will directly address the benefits of tDCS paired with CT. The ACT study is enrolling 360 older adults (ages 65-90) across 3 sites and uses multimodal neuroimaging, and neurocognitive and functional assessment to investigate tDCS related improvement in brain function and health. This trial aims to combat cognitive aging and slow progression of dementia. This talk will present our data on the benefits of tDCS for CT effects as well as describe the ongoing ACT trial. Results: We will present preliminary on the GABAergic and functional neural mechanisms of tDCS related benefits for CT and describe the overall design and methodology of the Phase III ACT trial. Discussion: As Phase III tDCS trials are a new yet obvious evolution for the field, dissemination of novel methods for implementation of studies of this scale will be important not only within the aging field, but across all areas of tDCS research that aim for clinically meaningful impact. Trials of this type stand to provide significant insight into the overall effectiveness and neural mechanisms underlying adjunctive tDCS effects for CT.
