N2  - Introduction: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) is considered an alternative for the improvement of cognition in elderly patients with cognitive impairment. A comprehensive systematic review with meta-analysis, which includes trials that involve all types of cognitive impairment, a criterion-based assessment of the risk of bias and the new trials, is prudent to provide up-to-date evidence on the effects of rTMS on cognitive function in elderly patients with cognitive impairment. Methods: We performed a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomised controlled trials from inception to May 2016. The primary outcome was cognitive function as measured by the Mini Mental State Examination or the Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale ecognitive subscale. Results: Seven randomised controlled trials were included in the metaanalysis, with a sample of 107 active and 87 sham rTMS procedures. Active rTMS was found to be more effective in improving cognition (Hedges' g, 0.48; 95% confidence interval, 0.12 to 0.84) - Fig.1. Subgroup analysis showed significant efficacy amongst subjects with concurrent psychotropic medications (Hedges' g, 0.63; 95% confidence interval, 0.05 to 1.20). Discussion: High-frequency rTMS showed a benefit on cognition amongst elderly patients with mild to moderate Alzheimer's disease and a good safety profile. A combination of rTMS and psychotropic medications is suggested to have an additional benefit. rTMS was shown to have great potential as an alternative intervention for cognition. Further research on the mechanism of effect, the optimal parameters and settings of rTMS and the effects of concurrent cognitive training or medications is important for the development of this new intervention in clinical practice. Figure 1. Meta-analysis of active vs. sham rTMS on improving cognition in elderly with cognitive impairment (Table Presented).
