N2  - Aware of the limitations in pharmacologic therapy, such as resistance, intolerance, partial response, contraindication and necessity of fast improvement, research in neuromodulation and neurostimulation have multiplied trying to find cost-effective and clinical relevant alternatives. Of note is the development and systematic use of Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation and other brain stimulation methods, such as deep brain stimulation, vagus nerve stimulation and trigeminal nerve stimulation. The current trial aims to design, assemble and clinically test a Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) device. This method is in frank development since de years 2000, being employed in psychiatric and cognitive disorders, such as depression, post stoke disability, anxiety, negative symptoms of schizophrenia, besides cognitive and memory enhancement. This study is a PhD project and has been approved by the local and national ethics committee. This trial will be divided in 2 phases: in the first phase, an electrical design will be developed and prototypes will be assembled, for further electrical certification. The authors aim to design and assemble a tDCS device with national technology, user-friendly interface, based on high standards of safety (redundancy of current control levels, timer, current and impedance control), following international specifications and recommendations (1 to 2 mA). In the second phase the clinical use will be assessed in a randomized controlled clinical trial in major depressive patients (anodal stimulation of left prefrontal dorsolateral cortex versus placebo). Improvement will be assessed through M.I.N.I., MADRS, BECK-D and WHO-QoL-BREF scales. In Brazil there are few centres offering these modalities of treatment, both in public or private sectors, and access is very restricted. Thus, this project is justified under the principles of providing care, improving access to technologies and validating a method to treat depression. In this poster the authors will present the electronic design, prototypes and clinical data from a pilot study.
