N2  - Background: More and more patients in Japan are having major or minor cognitive disorders. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has been reported to improve cognitive function in healthy subjects, but the effect of tDCS on cognitive function for patients with major cognitive disorder is not consistent among the studies. Objective: The objective of this study is to assess the safety and efficacy of tDCS during cognitive rehabilitation on cognitive function for patients with major or minor cognitive disorders. Method: A parallel, randomized, sham-controlled design is applied for 55- 90 years old outpatients or inpatients diagnosed as major or minor neurocognitive disorder in DSM-5 in a single center, the National Center of Neurology and Psychiatry. Participants, caregivers and raters are blinded to group assignment. Patricipants in the intervention group are receiving tDCS (anodal; F3, cathodal, Fp1, 2A, 20 min) twice a day for 5 consecutive days, while those in the control arm are taking sham-tDCS (anodal; F3, cathodal; Fp1, 2A, 40 sec) twice a day for the same period. Calculation task and reading task are conducted in both arms as a cognitive rehabilitation for 20 minutes during the stimulation (learning therapy). Patients with severe psychotic symptoms, severe depression, severe suicide ideation, or severe dementia with MMSE score of less than 18 points or Japanese version of Clnical Dementia Rating Scale(CDR-J) score of more than 3 points, are excluded. Participants are also excluded who could not safely conduct Electroconvulsive Therapy or tDCS or when they fails to score writing or drawing in mini mental state examination(MMSE). The primary outcome is dropout rate during the trial, which should not exceed 10% for safety reasons. Alzheimer Disease Assessment Scale - cognition, MMSE, Frontal Assessment Battery, CDR-J or its sum of boxes are assessed as secondary outcomes. The authors declare that they have no competing interests.
