N2  - Current treatments for morbid obesity (MO) are based on dietary intervention and bariatric surgery, without tackling behavioral alterations, although cognitive impairments involving executive functions (EF), such as working memory, decision-making and risk-taking behaviour have been reported in such subjects (Sellbom & Gunstad, 2012). Recent studies have found abnormal physiological activity in the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (ldlPFC), an area that supports reward-related aspects of eating behaviour and cognitive control (Alonso-Alonso 2013). Its relevance is supported by studies exploring the effect of tDCS in the PFC, reporting a reduction on food craving scores (Montenegro et al. 2012) and reduced calorie intake (Gluck et al. 2015). Here we change the SoA perspective to study the impact of tDCS over the ldlPFC combined with CT on EF performance. A total of twelveMO patients participated in a randomized, sham controlled study with 4 treatment sessions (20-min each). Anodal tDCS (1.5 mA) was applied on the rdlPFC (cathodal on the ldlPFC) using an optimized multi-electrode montage (Stimweaver, Ruffini et al., 2014). The normal component of electric field distribution is shown below. EEG was recorded before and after treatment using the same device (Starstim, Neuroelectrics). Despite the pilot small sample size, trends on variables related to flexibility, impulsivity and inhibitory control are observed, with the tDCS group committing less errors as subjects take more time before responding to the stimulus, differentially pre and post treatment. Additionally, this study analyzes within the EEG data the impact of the tDCS-CT in the oscillatory activity before and after the treatment and the connectivity among channels (analyzed in terms of coherence). In conclusion, tDCS combined with CT appears to have a positive effect on the cognitive impairments related to obesity and may provide a promising approach for treatment of MO patients. (Figure Presented) .
