N2  - Objective: To assess the safety and efficacy of multiple doses of pridopidine (45, 67.5, 90, 112.5 mg twice daily) in patients with Huntington disease (HD). Background: HD is fatal neurodegenerative disorder characterized by cognitive, motor, and behavioral features leading to long-term disability. Pridopidine, an investigational product, is a low-affinity dopamine type 2 receptor (D2R) antagonist and binds the sigma-1 receptor with high affinity (approximately 100-fold higher than D2R). It has demonstrated motor benefit in 2 randomized, double-blind clinical trials, MERMAID and HART. PRIDE-HD sought to evaluate efficacy and safety at doses higher than those used in prior studies. Methods: PRIDE-HD was a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled phase II study. Patients were randomized 1:1:1:1:1 to receive placebo or pridopidine (45, 67.5, 90, or 112.5 mg twice daily), titrated over 4 weeks and taken as full dose for 48 weeks. Efficacy was assessed throughout the 52-week period using Mixed Models Repeated Measures analyses of change from baseline in the Unified Huntington Disease Rating Scale (UHDRS) Total Motor Score (TMS), UHDRS-Behavioral, UHDRS-Cognitive, UHDRS-Total Functional Capacity, UHDRS-Functional Assessment, UHDRS-Independence Scale, the modified Physical Performance Test, individual TMS subscales, HDCognitive Assessment Battery, Problem-Based Assessment, and other outcomes. Adverse events, electrocardiogram data, labs, and vital signs were evaluated throughout the study. Pharmacokinetic data was collected throughout the study (plasma concentration). Results: In total, 408 patients were randomized. Twenty-six weeks of the study were completed by 323 patients, and 236 completed 52 weeks. Results of the study will be presented at the Huntington Study Group's annual meeting, HSG 2016. Conclusions: Results from PRIDE-HD support the continued clinical development of pridopidine as a treatment option for patients with HD.
