N2  - Objectives: The aim of this review is to determine the evidence for the use of rTMS to suppress visual hallucinations (VH) in patients suffering from Lewy body dementia (LBD). Background: LBD is a debilitating disease affecting approximately 1.4 million Americans. One characteristic symptom is the early appearance of debilitating VH. LBD patients are poor candidates for antipsychotics, with ∼50% showing severe EPS. Little is known about the pathogenesis of VH in LBD. Method: A search of PubMed was conducted utilizing the following: "transcranial magnetic stimulation visual hallucinations NOT auditory NOT verbal AND Humans AND English NOT schizophrenia," pointing to 5 articles. Results: There have been no randomized controlled studies evaluating the ability of rTMS to suppress VH in LBD. One study that used TMS to elicit phosphenes showed that cortical excitability was correlated with severity of VH in LBD. Another study correlating fMRI activation and TMS phosphene threshold showed that the visual cortex in LBD had a loss in inhibition which predisposed those with LBD to VH. A study of ecstasy users with TMS showed that phosphenes thresholds were lower than controls and in those ecstasy users with VH. In two case reports, rTMS was able to suppress VH secondary to occipital stroke and blindness. Conclusions: Little is known about the neurological circuitry involved in VH. Two studies showed changes in visual cortex excitability and inhibition. Two case reports showed success in suppressing VH with rTMS. Additional studies to assess the responsiveness of VH in patients with LBD are needed.
