N2  - Background: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has been shown to transiently alter cortical excitability and plasticity and shows promise as a potential therapeutic intervention for the treatment of cognitive deficits in a number of neuropsychiatric diseases. However, to date, these effects remain relatively modest and their underlying neurobiological mechanisms of action are still unclear. In the present study we explored both the behavioural and neurophysiological effects of tDCS as well as a more targeted form of stimulation (4x1-Ring HD-tDCS). Methods: 19 healthy adult participants were randomised to receive either tDCS, HD-tDCS or sham stimulation applied to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) over three separate testing sessions. Working memory (WM) performance (2-back task) and cortical excitability (TMS-EEG evoked potentials) were assessed before and after stimulation (1mA, 20 min) to assess for any cognitive and neurophysiological changes. Results: Following stimulation, participants receiving HD-tDCS demonstrated improved WM performance as indicated by faster reaction times on the 2-back task compared to baseline (p=.015), however no significant effect was seen for conventional tDCS (p>.05). TMS-evoked potentials also revealed a significant increase in cortical excitability, as indicated by larger P60 potential amplitudes following HD-tDCS (p=.038), but not tDCS (p<.05). Conclusions: Focal HD-tDCS over the left DLPFC was shown to both increase cortical excitability and improve WM performance. Further research investigating the use of such montages for cognitive enhancement is needed, particularly in clinical populations experiencing cognitive dysfunction. This study also demonstrates the feasibility of combining multimodal TMS-EEG imaging with tDCS.
