N2  - Objectives Deep brain stimulation in the subthalamic nucleus (DBS-STN) is a successful therapeutic approach to treat motor symptoms of Parkinson's disease. Because functional network changes underlying DBS STN are not well understood, we combined DBS-STN with functional [18F]FDG-PET in a rat hemiparkinson model. Methods Parkinson-like symptoms were induced by injecting 6-hydroxydopamine (6-OHDA) unilaterally into the medial forebrain bundle (n=7). Automated gait analysis and [18F]FDOPA PET confirmed motor impact and dopaminergic lesion, respectively. In sham operated controls (n=6), saline was injected instead of 6-OHDA. For DBS-STN an electrode was inserted through a chronically implanted guide cannula aiming at the ipsilesional STN. Two weeks after 6-OHDA or saline injection, [18F]FDG (2 mCi) was injected intraperitoneally, and immediately after injection awake and freely moving rats underwent one of two randomized stimulation conditions for 40 minutes: 1) DBS-STN with a pulse rate of 130 Hz (StimON); 2) Without electrode (StimOFF). 60 min after FDG injection, animals were anesthetized and a brain scan was acquired in a small animal PET scanner (Focus 220, Siemens). This procedure was repeated with the other stimulation condition on a different day. Seed-based functional connectivity analysis was performed with intra-individual difference images (StimON minus StimOFF). Results During StimOFF, hemiparkinson rats showed metabolic hypoactivity in the ipsilesional hemisphere as well as contralesional hyperactivity compared to controls. DBS-STN generally increased ipsilateral and decreased contralateral FDG uptake. Significant increases of metabolic activity during StimON were found in the ipsilateral prefrontal cortex, striatum, and deep cerebellar nuclei. FDG uptake decreased during StimON in the contralateral motor cortex, hippocampus, and thalamus. Functional connectivity analyses revealed a complex stimulation-associated bilateral network comprising thalamus, hippocampus, pons, and cerebellum. Striatum and globus pallidus externus formed a separate network, which was connected to the cerebellum via the pretectum. Conclusions Our study shows that DBS-STN normalizes the metabolic imbalance between hemispheres, which was initially caused by the dopaminergic lesion. Key areas were the deep cerebellar nuclei and thalamus, recruiting a network of associated brain regions.
