N2  - Objective: The study objective was to evaluate the safety and efficacy of Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) at the ventral capsule/ventral striatum (VC/VS) region to specifically modulate frontal lobe behavioral and cognitive networks as a novel treatment approach for AD patients. Background: Treatments for Alzheimer's disease (AD) are limited. Previously published investigations of DBS in AD have only targeted memory circuits. DBS to specifically modulate the frontal networks has never been performed but is a logical treatment approach as deficits in executive abilities, decisionmaking, and problem solving in AD patients, result in functional impairments and increased supervision needs that are very challenging for caretakers. Methods: This is a non-randomized phase I safety and pilot feasibility prospective open label interventional trial with matched comparison groups. AD participants given DBS for at least 18 months at the VC/VS target were compared on the Clinical Dementia RatingSum of Boxes (CDR-SB), our primary outcome clinical measure, to matched groups without DBS from the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) cohort. Results: Three AD DBS participants were matched to 13, 95, and 9 subjects respectively from the ADNI AD cohort. All participants tolerated DBS well without significant adverse events. All three AD DBS participants had less performance decline and two of them significantly less decline (p<0.05) after 18-28 months on our primary outcome measure, CDR-SB, relative to matched comparison groups from ADNI using score trajectory slopes. Conclusions: The first use of DBS in AD at a frontal lobe target (VC/VS) revealed preliminary findings of less performance decline in CDR-SB. Frontal network modulation to improve executive and behavioral deficits should be furthered studied in AD.
