N2  - Aims: To compare the efficacy of cognitive training (CT), transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), and cognitive training combined with tDCS for improving cognition in people with Parkinson's Disease and Mild Cognitive Impairment (PD-MCI). Methods: Participants were included if they met Movement Disorder Society Task Force Level II criteria for PD-MCI. Participants (N=42) were randomly allocated to one of six groups: (1) standard CT, (2) tailored CT, (3) tDCS, (4) standard CT+tDCS, (5) tailored CT+tDCS, or (6) a placebo-control group. Interventions lasted 4-weeks and participants' neuropsychological performance was measured at baseline, post-intervention (Week 5) and follow-up (Week 12). While controlling for moderator variables (e.g., education, disease duration), Generalized Linear Mixed Models (GLMMs) were used to analyze outcomes. Results: Compared to the control group: (1) executive function significantly improved in the standard CT+tDCS (p<.001) and tailored CT+tDCS (p=.024) groups, (2) attention/working memory significantly improved in the tDCS (p=.039) and standard CT+tDCS (p=.028) groups, (3) memory significantly improved in the tDCS (p<.001) and tailored CT+tDCS (p<.001) groups, (4) language significantly improved in the standard CT+tDCS (p=.008) and tailored CT+tDCS (p<.001) groups and (5) activities of daily living improved the standard CT (p<.001) and standard CT+tDCS (p=.014) groups. Conclusion: Cognitive training, tDCS and cognitive training combined with tDCS showed improvements in cognition and activities of daily living in people with PD-MCI.
