N2  - Objective: The aim of this study was to use graph theory analysis to examine the effects of seizure therapy on whole-brain network connectivity. Background: Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) has been reported to alter functional brain network architecture by down-regulating connectivity in frontotemporal circuits. Magnetic seizure therapy (MST), which induces therapeutic seizures with high-intensity repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation, was introduced to improve the seizure therapy risk/benefit ratio. Unfortunately, there is limited understanding of seizure therapy's underlying mechanisms of action. In particular, the change in brain network connectivity and organization for a single treatment session is not well understood. Methods: In this 2-center, double-masked study, patients were randomized to either ultrabrief pulse right unilateral ECT or circular coil MST. Topographical resting EEG was acquired within 30 minutes before and after the second treatment in 10 patients (3 MSTs and 7 ECTs). Functional connectivity was assessed using debiased weighted phase lag index, a measure of EEG phase synchronization. Brain network organization was assessed on the basis of the following graph theory measures: betweenness centrality, clustering coefficient, network density, and characteristic path length. Results: There was a significant posttreatment reduction in EEG phase synchronization in the beta frequency band. The posttreatment beta network also showed an aberration of the small-world architecture, as characterized by higher characteristic path length and lower clustering. Conclusions: The changes in network properties could be related to the acute cognitive impairment postseizure. Graph theoretical analysis of the topological organization of functional brain networks may provide insight into the mechanisms of seizure therapies.
