N2  - Objective: Schizophrenia is a debilitating, chronic psychiatric disease that affects approximately 1% of the population [1]. Cognitive deficits is central in schizophrenia and is among the strongest predictors of functionality. Although numerous antipsychotic medications are effective in treating positive symptoms, they do not have beneficial effects on cognition. Recently, repetitive trancranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has been proven as a practical and secure treatment modality that may have some positive effects on cognitive functions, such as working memory, in schizophrenia [1,2]. However, it is not clear whether rTMS has a similar effect on more complex cognitive functions such as strategic planning, organization, utilizing environmental feedback to shift cognitive sets, directing behavior toward achieving a goal, and modulating impulsive responding which are known as frontal lobe functions or executive functions, and can clinically be assessed byWisconsin Card Sorting Test (WCST) at schizophrenia patients who are known as having poorer performance than normal population [3]. The objective of this study is to explore the effect of bilateral high frequency rTMS on executive functions of schizophrenia patients. Method: In a 4-week randomized double-blind sham-controlled study design, 19 medicated schizophrenia patients from Sişli Hamidiye Etfal Training and Research Hospital were recruited between January and July 2014. Subjects with schizophrenia aged between 18 and 65 were included in the study if they had a Calgary Depression Scale (CDS) score of 11 or less, Standardized Mini- Mental State Examination (SMMSE) score of 24 or more and had Extrapyramidal Symptom Rating Scale score of 2 or less for each item. They were assessed by Positive and Negative Syndrome Scale (PANSS) and Scale for the Assessment of Negative Symptoms (SANS) before the treatment. After randomization of the patients as active or sham rTMS group, they performed WCST before and after rTMS targeted bilaterally sequentially to left and right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) 1000 pulses/side at 20 Hz for 20 treatments. Results: There were no significant difference between schizophrenia groups in respect to sociodemographic and clinical status, and mean scores of CDS, SMMSE, PANSS and SANS (p >0.05). No significant difference between the groups in respect to each post-treatment WCST mean score was observed. Besides, there was a slight but not significant improvement in pre- and post-treatment WCST mean score changes, except number of categories completed which had been worse by the treament in both groups (p>0.05). Conclusion: This study suggests that bilateral high frequency rTMS may not have a positive effect on WCST performance of schizophrenia patients. Of one rationale may be that because WCST measures multiple complex cognitive functions and so, beside DLPFC, many cortical and subcortical regions must be activated during the test porformance [4]. This suggests that, simply activating DLPFC region may not be adequate in order to improve the test performance in schizophrenia patients [5] and furthermore, different rTMS application procedures may be investigated, as well. However, this data must be replicated by studies with larger populations.
