N2  - Purpose of the study: Schizophrenia presents wide and wellestablished cognitive deficits, nowadays considered a core feature of the disease, with a great impact on the global functioning. Neuroanatomically cognitive performance seems to be mainly related with the functioning of the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC), proved to be altered in schizophrenia. Although reducing positive symptoms and partially negative symptoms, first and second generation antipsychotics insufficiently impact on cognitive deficits. Neuropsychological strategies has been developed over the years in order to improve cognitive performances. The most diffused one, namely Cognitive Remediation Therapy (CRT), demonstrated a good efficacy on cognitive deficits and global functioning, although results are still heterogeneous [1]. Recently, techniques of physical neurostimulation have been proposed. The transcranial direct current stimulation (t-DCS) is one of the most studied to improve cognitive deficit, initially in the neurological field. Dorsolateral prefrontal cortex anodal stimulation has been shown to improve many different cognitive domains, both in healthy subjects, neurological and psychiatric patients, however major issues are still maintenance over time and generalization of the effects [2]. On the basis of the evidence reported, we hypothesize that anodal t-DCS can produce an anticipation and/or enhancement of CRT effects on cognitive impairments associated with schizophrenia. Methods: 20 patients diagnosed with schizophrenia, according to DSM VI-TR, have been included in the study and were randomized to active or sham tDCS, plus a short-track CRT (15 sessions - three per week - instead of 30). The tDCS was performed twice a day for twenty minutes each, for ten working days. All patients started the CRT protocol at the same time as tDCS. The anodal electrode was positioned on the left DLPFC and the cathodal electrode was positioned on the right fronto-orbitarian cortex, according to the protocol demonstrated more effective in the literature [3]. For the active group, the tDCS current intensity was 2 mA. 7 patients completed the active tDCS, while 8 the sham tDCS. All patients were assessed by means of the Brief Assessment of Cognition in Schizophrenia (BACS), pre and post treatment, to evaluate the effects on cognitive domains. Summary of results: The comparison of effect sizes of improvement in each cognitive domain between the two groups by means of Mann-Whitney U Test, found a significant difference only for Verbal Memory performance (p<0.001). Patients treated with active tDCS showed a greater improvement only in Verbal Memory, while domains resulted non significantly affected by the neurostimulation. Conclusions: tDCS seems to have an effect on cognitive domains, specifically on Verbal Memory, known to be only partially improved by CRT. The lack of significant effects on other domains may be due to the short duration of CRT. While showing only a little effect of anticipation on CRT, tDCS associated with a standard Cognitive Remediation may prove a valid, non-invasive, technique for treatment of cognitive deficits schizophrenia.
