N2  - Background: Interventions to prevent Alzheimer's Dementia (AD) are urgently needed. We propose to study the efficacy of an intervention in three high risk groups: (1) older persons with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI); (2) older persons with a major depressive disorder (“late-life depression” - LLD) without MCI; and (3) older persons with LLD and MCI. Methods: Our proposed intervention is a combination of cognitive remediation (CR) and transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS). Subjects with MCI or LLD will be randomized to CR + tDCS or sham-CR + sham-tDCS. Both CR and tDCS have been shown to induce neuroplasticity and improve cognition. We hypothesize that their combination will enhance cognitive compensation and protect against cognitive decline. Results: Over 24 months, five Toronto academic sites will enroll: (1) 125 non-depressed subjects age 60 and older who present with MCI; (2) 125 non-demented subjects age 65 and older who present without MCI but with LLD; and (3) 125 non-demented subjects age 65 and older who present with MCI and LLD. These 375 subjects will be randomized under double-blind conditions to receive CR + tDCS or sham-CR + sham-tDCS and followed for 30 to 59 months. The two primary aims are to compare the efficacy of CR + tDCS vs. sham + sham in: (1) preventing long-term cognitive decline; (2) preventing the incidence of dementia. Conclusions: If we are successful in this high risk population, then CR + tDCS can be tested in, and extended to, the general population.
