N2  - Introduction: Spatial navigation is essential in everyday life but declines with “normal” aging and further in neurodegenerative disease. Previous neuroimaging work suggests that these behavioral changes may arise, in part, from reduced parietal lobe functioning. The current study used a randomized, double-blind, crossover design to examine the effects of high-definition (HD)tDCS on spatial navigation using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI). Methods: Twelve cognitively intact older adults completed 3 sessions in which they received 20 minutes of anodal, cathodal, or sham HD-tDCS (2mA) over site Pz. The order was counterbalanced across subjects. During subsequent fMRI scanning (approximately 20 minutes after stimulation), participants were instructed to form mental maps while they viewed videos showing navigation through complex environments. Participants then completed memory testing in which they recalled the location of key environmental landmarks using a touch screen monitor. This approach allowed us to quantify the magnitude of inaccuracy (i.e., cm from actual target location) and examine the relationship between behavioral performance and fMRI activation. Results: Relative to sham, anodal stimulation increased activation in the precuneus as measured via both contrast- and correlationbased analyses. This replicates our earlier findings with young adults and suggests this region plays an important role in mental map formation and use; consonant with its role in internally directed cognition. In contrast, cathodal stimulation increased activation in the left inferior parietal lobule relative to sham while correlational analyses revealed an increased relationship between behavior and prefrontal activation. This pattern of correlated results differed substantially from both anodal and sham stimulation and suggests that parietal “suppression” facilitates the recruitment of extended neural networks in a potentially compensatory manner. Discussion: These findings suggest HD-tDCS modulates both local and distributed neural networks depending on stimulation polarity. Ongoing work is examining these effects in patients with early Alzheimer's disease to establish HD-tDCS's therapeutic value.
