N2  - Subthalamic nucleus deep brain stimulation (STN DBS) is an important therapy for Parkinson's disease, by altering the function of the basal ganglia which play an important role in controlling saccades. The aim of the study is to evaluate latency, time of duration, velocity and amplitude of random prosaccades (RS) in patients with Parkinson's disease who underwent STN DBS of L-DOPA medication and deep brain stimulation (DBS) on motor impairment, functional disability, cognitive impairment, and behavioural abnormalities of DBS therapy in patients with Parkinson's disease (PD) using the Unified PD Rating Scale (UPDRS). RS in horizontal eye movement measurements were recorded by head-mounted saccadometer (Ober Consulting, Poland) postoperatively in 28 STN DBS patients with idiopathic Parkinson's disease (mean age 52±10,3years) in four sessions: S1: Stim- OFFMedOFF, S2: StimOFFMedON, S3: StimONMedOff, S4: Stim- ONMedON. Motor examination, behavioral dysfunction, cognitive impairment and functional disability were evaluated in each session according to the UPDRS scale. We observed statistically significant correlations between mean RS latency and the session of examination: S1 - 336,56 ms, S2 - 351,72ms, S3 - 282,51ms, S4 - 263,34ms. Other parameters of RS (velocity, amplitude, time of duration) were also different in all sessions, but were not statistically significant (p>0.05). The latency of RS was also correlated with motor examination in UPDRS III score and with total UPDRS score (p<0.05). Our research suggest that RS measurement is correlated with motor examination of STN DBS PD patients. Therefore it can be an useful tool in monitoring of the disease progression as well as influence of DBS on the individual patient's motor capability.
