N2  - Background: Previous studies have suggested that Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) for Parkinson's disease (PD) causes weight gain. This study analyzes changes in Body Mass Index (BMI) in subjects with early stage PD treated with bilateral subthalamic nucleus DBS over a two-year followup period. Methods: Twenty-nine subjects with early stage PD (age 50-75, H&Y II off medication, treated with antiparkinsonian medications for≥6 months but < 4 years, and lacking motor fluctuations, dyskinesias, and dementia) completed a prospective, randomized, single-blind clinical trial comparing optimal drug therapy (ODT) (n=14) to DBS+ODT (n=15). The weight of each subject was recorded at baseline and at 6, 12, 18, and 24-month follow-up visits. BMIs for each subject were calculated following the conclusion of the study. Results: At baseline, the average BMI was 29.7 in the ODT group and 32.3 in the DBS+ODT group. The change in BMI from baseline to 24 months was not statistically significant between the two groups (p=0.52, ODT= 20.89; DBS+ODT= 20.17). CONCLUSION: This study suggests that DBS is not associated with weight gain in subjects with early stage PD.
