N2  - Background: Upper limb dysfunction is one of the most prevalent impairments following spinal cord injury (SCI). Although various rehabilitative programs are employed, benefit is weak and variable. Their limited success may relate to maladaptive changes in the brain; in the primary motor cortex (M1), maps devoted to less affected parts of paretic limb expand at the expense of more affected. We hypothesize rehabilitative outcomes may be augmented if adaptive plasticity is instead enhanced; one such adjunctive method may involve brain stimulation using non-invasive transcranial direct current (tDCS). Objective: To examine whether tDCS applied to M1 enhances rehabilitative outcomes of the paretic upper limb in incomplete quadriplegia by augmenting plasticity of motor maps, studied using transcranial magnetic stimulation. Design: Randomized-controlled, two-group, repeated-measures. Methods: Following a 2-week control period, patients with cervical SCI are assigned to receive either rehabilitation paired with tDCS or rehabilitation paired with sham. Rehabilitation involves functional activities involving more affected parts of paretic upper limbs. Measures include dexterity, grasp, grip, strength, and mapping. Patients with incomplete SCI with incomplete injury from C2 to C7 at least 6 months prior are included. The exclusionary criteria are cardiac pacemaker, metal in head, seizures, neuro- or psycho-active medications, pregnancy, implanted pumps, shunts, neurostimulators, or other neurological condition as brain tumor, dementia, substance abuse, or stroke. Results: We report findings from a 52-year-old man with incomplete C2 injury who received tDCS during rehabilitation. At first, he showed greater weakness of left shoulder/upper arm than hand/wrist. After training, he demonstrated 9% change on dexterity and 50% improvement for strength (grasp, grip, and proximal shoulder). As strength of more affected deltoid/biceps recovered (2- to 2+ on motor score), that of less affected index finger/thumb recovered as well (2+ to 4). Maps of deltoid, trained extensively during tDCS, enlarged and shifted towards that of hand and increased overlap. Conclusions: Our case finding from ongoing study suggests that stimulation may facilitate outcomes of concurrent rehabilitation involving more affected muscles. Although preliminary, findings indicate that gains may be explained by adaptive reorganization in M1 - greater cooperation between maps of more and less affected parts rather than maladaptation.
