N2  - Objective: The primary objective of this study is to assess the efficacy and dose response of pridopidine 45 to 112.5 mg twice daily (bid) on motor impairment in patients with HD after 26 weeks of treatment using the Unified Huntington's Disease Rating Scale (UHDRS) Total Motor Score (TMS). Background: Huntington's disease (HD) is a neurodegenerative disorder with an autosomal dominant mode of inheritance, associated with a triad of motor, behavioral, and cognitive symptoms and signs. Pridopidine is a dopamine stabilizer and is believed to both enhance and counteract dopamine dependent functions in the central nervous system depending on the initial level of dopaminergic activity and to bind with high affinity to sigma-1 receptors. As previously indicated in two clinical studies in HD patients, pridopidine may improve motor impairment, with potentially increased effects at higher dosages. Methods: This is a multinational, randomized, parallel-group, double-blind, placebo-controlled study to compare the efficacy and safety of pridopidine in the treatment of motor impairment in HD. It is planned to enroll a total of 400 patients (80 patients per treatment arm). Patients will be randomized (1:1:1:1:1) to receive pridopidine 45, 67.5, 90, or 112.5 mg or placebo bid for 26 weeks, including a 4-week progressive titration period. The primary endpoint for this study is change from baseline in the UHDRS-TMS at week 26. Physical performance test (PPT) is being assessed as secondary endpoint to evaluate global and functional impact of pridopidine treatment. A number of additional clinical measures are being analyzed as exploratory endpoints, including complementary motor assessments. PK and safety will be evaluated. Conclusions: There is a significant unmet medical need to ameliorate symptoms of HD. This study will provide essential data towards possible effective and safe use of pridopidine for HD patients. Enrollment for this study will start in Q1 2014.
