N2  - Objective: To investigate the effects of transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) in not-demented patients with Parkinson's disease (PD) complicated by drug-resistant freezing of gait (FOG), through placebo-controlled study. Background: Progression of PD is characterized by motor and cognitive deficits which eventually respond less to dopaminergic therapy. Non-invasive brain stimulation has shown promising results and may provide a therapeutic alternative, but no evidences are available. Methods: Seven patients (3 men; age560.9(9 SD); disease duration=516.8(4 SD)) underwent a session of 2.0 mA tDCS and a sham-stimulation, both delivered to the prefrontal cortex, at least 30 days apart from each other (the starter session was selected randomly); both the right and left hemispheres were separately stimulated, for 20 minutes each. Exclusion criteria were cognitive impairment (MMSE ≤24). The outcome measures were the following: UPDRS-motor part (UPDRSm), Timed Up and Go (TUG), TUG with motor dual task (TUGm), TUG with cognitive dual task (TUGc), digit span (forward and backward - DSf, DSb), Corsi's spatial span (forward and backward- SSf, SSb), phonetic verbal fluency (PVF), semantic verbal fluency (SVF) and STROOP test (ST). The measures were assessed immediately before and at the end of the stimulation. Results: After the bilateral prefrontal tDCS, a significant improvement of the following measures were observed: UPDRSm (Z=-2;p=.04), TUG (Z=-2.2;p=.02), TUGc (Z=-2.2;p=.02), DSb (Z=-2;p=.04) and STROOP time (Z=-2;p=.04). No significant changes of the outcome measures were found, in the same patients, when a sham-stimulation has been delivered. Conclusions: tDCS, delivered bilaterally on the prefrontal cortex of patients with PD, can exert a beneficial effect on both motor (in particular on the axial features) and cognitive symptoms (in particular on attention and working memory). This findings may be useful in order to cope with FOG.
