N2  - Objective: The aims of our double blind study are:1) to test whether t-DCS of left DLPFC enhances the effect of CT on cognitive performance in PD-CI. 2) to investigate with MRI whether cognitive improvements are associated with discrete regional modifications of brain perfusion and cortical excitability. Background: The effect of computer-based cognitive training (CT) alone or in association with non-invasive brain stimulation (t- DCS) of left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) in PD patients with Cognitive Impairments (PD-CI) is debated. Methods: Sixteen PD-CI (mean age of 69.87 ys and education of 8.81 ys) randomly received 4-week trial of CT (4 times per week) paired with 20 minutes sham or real anodal t-DCS over left DLPFC. Executive-attentional tasks (planning, problem-solving, allertness, visuo-motor coordination)were administered at each CT session. Patients underwent a structural volumetric as well as functional MRI (1.5 T scanner) at study entry and 48 hours after study end along with an extensive clinical (mean disease duration of 9.12 ys), cognitive-behavioral (MoCA, RBANS, BDI-II, STAI Y-1) examination. Results: The whole PD-CI group significantly increased their performance at fronto-striatal based cognitive tests during computerbased treatment (p<0.000). Within subjects analysis showed significant increase at MoCA and delayed memory scores (p<0.05), and significant decrease at BDI-II score (p<0.01)after treatment. Fractional Amplitude of Low-Frequency Fluctuation (fALFF) of the resting state fMRI signal showed that DLPFC, Pre-Supplementary Motor Area (Pre-SMA), Orbitofrontal Cortex (OFC), Anterior Cingulate Cortex (ACC), and cerebellum areas had significantly higher fALFF after treatment. Conclusions: Specific non-pharmacologic therapeutic strategies can ameliorate cognition (mainly global cognitive status and recall memory processes) and behavioural outcome (enhancing mood) in PD-CI. Moreover, attentional-executive training seems to be associated with increased functional activity in networks involved in attention-decision making (DLPFC, Pre-SMA, OFC, ACC) and coordination (cerebellum). In addition no significant reduction was observed as associated with cognitive treatment. These findings may help to clarify the mechanisms underlying potential benefit of computer-based CT and encourage its use in PD cognitive rehabilition programs. (Figure Presented).
