N2  - Parkinson Disease (PD) is a chronic degenerative disorders with motor and non-motor symptoms. According to the clinical response to therapies we recognize three stages of disease. The first one is the so called“HoneyMoon” stage, when the patient shows slight well controlled motor symptoms with dopaminergic medications with a perfect quality of life and no limitation in daily or professional activities. The second stage shows motor fluctuations plus drug related dyskinesia. During this stage the professional and daily activities suffer due to the involuntary movements and lost of mobility with an increasing disability. Features of the third stage are usually cognitive and behavioral disorders which induce severe disability with necessity of long term assistance. The Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) is widely considered an effective therapy for Parkinsonian patients with motor symptoms induced by the prolonged medical therapy. For instance the Subthalamus Nucleus Stimulation (STN-DBS), imitates the L-dopa effects on motor symptoms (Rigidity, Hypokinesia, Tremor), but with a better impact on adverse events and quality of life (3,5,13,21,22). However, DBS is currently recommended only for the late stages of PD(8-15 years from the onset). The first reason to use DBS as a delayed treatment is the invasiveness of the surgical technique, especially because no significant neuro-protective effects have been reported. Moreover a clear diagnosis of some atypical patients, is possible only after 4-5 years from the onset, showing in these cases a very poor prognosis and scarce response to DBS (2,15). Some recent clinical trials studied the effect of the early treatment with DBS compared to medical therapy in patients with early diagnosis of PD. The early treatment with DBS during the beginning of the second stage of disease (4-6 years after the onset) could improve the quality of life of these patients prolonging the therapeutic effect, reducing the drugs intake and retarding the stage of severe disability(1,4,14,16,17,18). Schupbach et al (18) published in 2007 the first controlled randomized trial on 20 patients demonstrating the positive impact of early DBS compared to medical therapy. In 2013 (16) a randomized multicenter trial compared 116 patients treated with STN-DBS against 110 patients treated with the best medical therapy. The inclusion criteria requested were: randomization of the patients 6weeks before; ages between 18-60 years; clinical evaluation with Hoehn-Yahr and UPDRS scales; duration of disease ≥ 4 years; onset of motor symptoms between 6 months and 3 years and optimal response to an equivalent intake of L-Dopa (4,16). Patients with dementia, depression, acute psychosis and other significant comorbidities were excluded. Patients surgically treated, underwent a bilateral STN-DBS under local anesthesia, with neurophysiological monitoring. The post operative CT or MRI demonstrated the correct electrodes' positioning. As commonly accepted for medical trials in PD, the primary endpoint for the outcome was PDQ-39 (motion, daily activities, emotional status, stigma, social support, communication and cognitive abilities) which computes subjective feeling about personal life. As secondary outcome scales the UPDRS II-III e IV, SCOPA-PS score and the equivalent L-dopa dose were accepted. All the patients were evaluated by a physician neurologist before the randomization and after 5, 12 e 24 months with video-UPDRS-III, and standard neurological exam for rigidity. Results demonstrated the crucial role of DBS compared to medical therapy in the majority of items (PDQ-39), with a 26% increase of main improvement; the maximal efficacy was reached after 24 months. The efficacy on motor items was actually equivalent between the two groups during the best “ON” period, the “freezing” and akinetic time at day were decreased only in DBS patients (2,16,19). On the other hand DBS group showed 54.8% of adverse events (surgery related in 17.7% or stimulation related). The main adverse events reported for the group treated with medical therapy were motor disorders, hallucinations and behavioral disturbances. Two suicides occurred in the DBS group. Even if the rate of adverse events resulted higher than in other published studies, no statistical significance was reported. Among the surgical related adverse events, hemorrhages didn't occur compared to the reported 1% found in the major case series. Two cerebral abscess were reported for the first time compared to the other main European case series (2,8,16). However the type and incidence of adverse events was comparable to the previous published data(2,9,20). Significant criticism have been placed on this study about methodological considerations, type of follow-up and adverse events. For instance the main age of the patients was 53 years, which can correspond to a peculiar sub-population of PD patients with early onset and some phenotypical and genotypical features which in this case couldn't represent the whole PD population (2,8,9). Some authors believe that these features could have strongly affected the final results. Another criticism regards the duration of disease higher than 4 years. In some cases, the correct diagnosis of PD could be wrong within the first five years of disease even in expert hands (15). Moreover, the results from primary outcome based on PDQ-39 could be affected by the knowledge of the DBS patients about the different treatment they received, compared to the other group. Furthermore the clinical evaluation was performed in all the cases with active stimulation (ON), which could have generated some bias related to the different expectations during the personal evaluation (8,9). Finally, even if the neurological exam was conducted with a blind evaluation during the video-UPDRS-III, in the same way could be less objective during the rigidity examination on each patient (8). Among the results, the 26% of PDQ-39 improvement is actually comparable to the 24% reported by the main case series with long term results in DBS patients lately treated (the main duration of disease was 13 years). In this case the follow-up period (2 years) is definitely not enough to claim a prolonged and better efficacy fromthe early DBS (2,6,9,10). Only a long term follow-up could confirm results about the duration of intermediate period of disease and adverse events. Shalash et al published in 2013 a retrospective not randomized study on PD patients treated with STN-DBS, subdivided into two groups whichwere treated in early stages of disease and a second group treated in later stage of disease. The mean follow up period was 5 years. The UPDRS-III improvement and the same rate of surgical complications were reported in both groups without differences. On the other hand, the DBS improved the behavioral and cognitive aspects only in younger patients compared to the cognitive decline described in the elderly population. The only correlation to the duration of disease was reported for the axial symptoms which are commonly related to the Med OFF-Stim ON and Med ON-Stim-ON periods (19). A remarkable DBS complication is the higher rate of suicide (2 over 116 in the DBS group, 1 over 110 in the other group). The DBS effect on depression is still a matter of debate (2,16,19). The Earlystim study reported an higher incidence of depression in DBS patients compared to emotional disturbances and psychosis, more frequent in the patients treated with medical therapy. According to Shalash, after the STN-DBS symptoms of depression were higher in patients younger than 55 years, but no suicides were reported. Hence the younger age category was a crucial factor for the outcome rather than the duration of disease, maybe because of the professional and sociocultural expectations (10,11,1719). Finally, the health assistance cost seemed to be more convenient in DBS patients which experienced 277 accesses to clinics or hospitals, versus the 343 for the group treated with medical therapy. Actually, this trend doesn't take into account the indirect costs due to surgical revisions of the DBS implant, IPG replacements and the surgical treatment of adverse events (2,8,9). Concluding, the Early Stim study supports the possibility to preserve or prolong a good quality of life in PD patients via the STN DBS in the early stage of disease, before the motor complications L-Dopa related. A better therapeutic impact for DBS compared to the best medical treatment has been demonstrated in early and delayed stages of the disease (2,14- 16,19,21,22). The short follow-up period is unfortunately a significant limitation in order to accept these results. Only a long term follow-up with several surgical targets compared could confirm the durability of the therapeutic effect. This would have a crucial impact on patients' quality of life and on the natural history of Parkinson disease as well. This “Second Therapeutic honey Moon”, would prolong the intermediate stage of disease, at the same time would decrease the incidence of adverse events and postpone severe disability (5,9,12,13,15). However patients' selection after only a few years of disease could be dangerous for patients with atypical Parkinsonism with the high risk for them to undergo unnecessary and invasive treatment, also with an important economic impact (15). A recent study from Charles et al of the Nashville group, supported the possible use of DBS in patients enrolled within 2 years from the diagnosis, with an even higher risk of ineffective treatment (1). At this time, DBS for early stage of PD is not approved in USA either (2).
