N2  - Introduction: DBS in HD was evaluated in a prospective pilot trial. Primary endpoint results after a preceding randomised cross-over period each for 6 weeks of either internal (GPI) or external (GPE) pallidum, and after 3 months of best contact stimulation showed significant suppression of chorea. Long-term effects on cognition, mood, and quality of life will be reported after 12 months of follow-up. Methods: Six HD-patients (2 westphal variants) were examined. The following outcome parameters were assessed at 12 months follow-up and were compared with pre-operative baseline: Unified Huntington's Disease Rating Scale (UHDRS), UHDRS chorea subscore, Burke-Fahn-Marsden Dystonia Rating Scale (BFMDRS), Unified-Parkinson's Disease Rating Scale (UPDRS-III), Mattis Dementia Rating Scale, Becks Depression Inventory (BDI), Huntington's Disease Activity of Daily-Living (HD-ADL), and quality of life SF-36 score. Results: UDHRS motor score changed from 55 (SD18) to 53 (SD 25), n.s. Excluding westphal patients from analysis, UHDRS motor score change was significant [47 (SD 15) to 36 (SD 12), p <0.05, n =4]. The same was true for the chorea subscore [9 (SD 8) to 4 (SD 4), p <0.1, n =6 and 13 (SD 4) to 6 (SD2), p =0.05, for n =4 respectively]. BFMDRS und UPRDS results were heterogeneous: scores generally worsened over the whole group but improved n.s in the non-westphal group. BDI, Mattis, and HD-ADL were stable. SF-36 vitality and mental health improved significantly (p <0.05). Three serious adverse events occurred: 1 pneumonia/sepsis, 1 traumatic subdural haematoma with non-convulsive status epilepticus, and 1 death due to aspiration pneumonia following epistaxis. None of the SAE were judged as treatment related. Conclusion: This is the first prospective pilot trial reporting DBS in HD. Long-term effects after 12 months follow-up show stable suppression of chorea, no deterioration in mood and cognition, and significant improvement in SF-36 vitality and mental health quality of life assessments. Distinct motor effects, for example on dystonia and functional relevance of DBS on quality of life, should be addressed in a larger multicentre and sham-stimulation-controlled trial.
