N2  - INTRODUCTION: Over 33% of patients with epilepsy experience persistent cognitive deficits in learning and memory that may involve hippocampal pathways. Using a pilocarpine-induced status epilepticus (SE) rodent model of epilepsy, we investigated the relationship between hippo-campal theta oscillations and cognitive performance, and tested our hypothesis that deep brain stimulation of the medial septal nucleus (MSN) input to the hippocampus will improve theta activity and learning and memory. METHODS: Sixty-three adult male Sprague-Dawley rats (300-350 grams) were injected with pilocarpine (n = 32) or saline (n = 31), and bipolar microelectrodes were stereotactically implanted into the MSN and hippocampus. Rats received MSN theta stimulation (7.7 Hz 80 μA; Sham, n = 16; pilocarpine, n = 14) or no stimulation (Sham, n = 16; pilocarpine, n = 17) during an object exploration (post-injection day (PID) 7) and Barnes Maze task (PID 12-14). Video-EEG recordings were obtained during each behavioral task. RESULTS: Rats that experienced SE had significantly decreased percent time in hippocampal theta during both cognitive tasks (P < .05), but had no differences in percent time in MSN theta (P = .39) or MSN-hippocampal theta phase coherence (P = .48). SE animals had significant deficits in the object exploration task and required more time to find the Barnes maze escape box. In the Barnes maze task, SE animals persisted in the use of a non-spatial, random strategy. SE rats that received MSN theta stimulation experienced significant improvements in object exploration and Barnes maze task performance. On the Barnes maze, while SE utilized a predominantly random strategy, stimulation of SE rats normalized the search strategy such that it was similar to that of Sham controls. CONCLUSION: Following SE, rats had significantly reduced hippo-campal theta oscillations that correlated with cognitive dysfunction. Deep brain MSN theta stimulation improved object exploration and spatial memory performance, suggesting that MSN deep brain stimulation may be an effective therapy to improve cognitive performance in patients with epilepsy.
