N2  - Objective: To explore healthcare utilization involving cognitiverelated diagnoses and medications before and after deep brain stimulation (DBS) surgery in the VA CSP-468 Parkinson's disease (PD) cohort, which compared globus pallidus interna (GPi) and subthalamic nucleus (STN) deep brain stimulation (DBS) procedures. Background: Although cognitive and neuropsychiatric changes in post-DBS PD patients are recognized, the related VA-based diagnostic codes and medications patterns are not well studied. Methods: In a subsample of 161 VA-based subjects randomized to STN (76) or GPi (85) DBS and followed for 36 months, data regarding cognitive deficit-related ICD-9 diagnoses and treatment with cognitive medications was extracted from VA administrative databases. Results: 19 subjects had at least one cognitive diagnosis 6 months prior to surgery. 31 additional subjects had a healthcare utilization visit associated with a cognitive diagnosis by 36 months. The variety of cognitive-related diagnoses post-operatively increased with time: at baseline there were = different diagnoses, with 9 more diagnoses recorded by 36 months. The most common diagnosistic entry was the non-specific “Mental Disorder Not Otherwise Specified (MDNOS)” (46.6%). The prevalence of reported cognitive diagnoses was not different between these two surgical groups at 36 months (p = 0.35). Cognitive medications prescriptions increased over time, with 2 medications pre-surgery and 14 at 36 months. Only 24.3% of subjects with a cognitive diagnosis were prescribed a cognitive medication. Conclusions: This VA-based utilization database documents an increase in number and diversity of cognitive diagnoses over time following DBS surgery, with equal frequency in both surgical groups. Post-operative problems, medication changes, or natural disease progression may explain these findings. “Parkinson's disease dementia” was not an available code, and therefore PD-related cognitive deficits are variously coded. Future efforts for a consensus on coding could help study long-term outcomes with greater clarity.
