N2  - Objective: To evaluate the temporal course and magnitude of placebo and treatment effects of UHDRS-Total Motor Score (TMS) in clinical studies testing therapeutic interventions in HD. Background: There is currently no approved disease modifying treatment or intervention that provides cross-domain symptomatic control in HD. Several marketed and experimental compounds have been tested and with the exception of tetrabenazine for HD chorea, have shown conflicting results. Better understanding of the placebo effect in HD clinical research may help improve future trial design. Methods: All randomized, double blinded, placebo-controlled clinical trials conducted in HD patients were searched within MEDLINE, EMBASE, BIOSIS, and DERWENT. Fourteen studies representing 1821 subjects measuring UHDRS TMS were available. The analyses were based on study level data weighted by sample size. Placebo and treatment effects were best modeled as presented in Figure 1. Results: Maximal placebo and treatment effects on TMS were estimated to be the similar; -5.3 units (95% CI: -7.7 to -3.0), occurring around 2.3 months. Natural disease progression rate was estimated to be 6 units/year (95% CI: 5.6 to 6.4). We subsequently conducted a sub-analysis on clinical trials aiming at motor symptomatic improvement as a primary endpoint. The parameter estimates were similar to initial estimates. Limited longitudinal data available for sub-analysis resulted in model instability and inability to reliably calculate confidence intervals of the model parameters. Conclusions: The analysis provides model-based estimates of natural disease progression, placebo and treatment effects on TMS in patients with HD. The results could be used for supporting future study designs, especially endpoint selection, study duration, and sample size calculation.
