N2  - Objectives: Freezing of gait (FoG) is a highly disabling symptom of Parkinson's disease (PD) characterized by a sudden disruption of gait pattern which causes brief and episodic absence of forward progression of the feet during walking. Generally, pharmacological treatments have poor efficacy while rehabilitation seems to have an important role in reducing FoG phenomena. Among rehabilitation strategies, cueing and treadmill training (TT) are considered the best practice but programs based on neurocognitive rehabilitation aimed at improving motor planning by using motor imagery (NR-MI) have never been tested so far. We wanted to test the efficacy of NR-MI in reducing FoG, as compared with TT. Methods: 14 PD patients with FoG and no evidence of dementia (MMSE>24) or depression (BDI<16) were enrolled and randomly assigned to two treatment groups. Group 1 performed 20 sessions of NR-MI, while Group 2 underwent 20 sessions of TT. Disease stage (H&Y and UPDRS III), disability (MPAS), FoG (FOGQ), quality of life (PDQ-39) were assessed at baseline, at the end of the rehabilitation program (T1), 1 month (T2), and 3 months after treatment (T3). At baseline, patients underwent also a brief neuropsychological testing to asses mainly frontal and executive functions. Furthermore, patients were studied before and after treatment with single and paired pulse transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) to investigate possible changes in primary motor cortex excitability. Results: At baseline, the two groups did not differ for any considered variable. At T1 evaluation, Group 1 showed significantly lower scores of FoGQ and higher scores of MPAS compared to Group 2. Goup differences in FoGQ score were maintained at T2 evaluation. Comparing T1 and T2 evaluations with baseline scores, a significant reduction of FoGQ score was found for group 1, whereas no differences were detectable for group 2. TMS suggested a tendency toward an increase in the excitability of the motor cortex after both treatments with respect to baseline indexes of intracortical inhibition and facilitation, and of threshold and recruitment curves. Conclusions: Patients treated with NR-MI experienced a significant improvement of FoG, while patients treated with TT did not show any significant benefit. NR-MI apperas to be an interesting rehabilitation strategy to treat FoG in PD patients.
