N2  - William M. McDonald, MD is the JB Fuqua Chair for Late-Life Depression at Emory University Chair of the APA Task Force on ECT and has recently completed an NIMH sponsored research study in transcranial magnetic stimulation (OPT-TMS). Charles H. Kellner, MD is Professor of Psychiatry and Director of the Division of Geriatric Psychiatry at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine and Director of the ECT service at the Mount Sinai Hospital in New York City. Dr. Kellner's talk will take the principles outlined by Dr. McDonald and discuss new research that highlights the effect of electrode placement and stimulus intensity on both antidepressant efficacy and cognitive effects of ECT. We present data on the relative merits of bilateral versus ultrabrief pulse right unilateral ECT in the elderly from an NIMH study. Current treatment recommendations and areas in need of further study will be discussed. Georgios Petrides, MD is an Associate Professor of Psychiatry at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine and Director of ECT Research at the Zucker Hillside Hospital. Dr. Petrides will review the data on the efficacy of ECT in psychotic disorders including psychotic depression in the elderly including data from an NIMH trial. Elderly patients fared better than younger patients and the same was the case for elderly psychotic patients vs younger psychotic patients. Robert Greenberg, MD is Chief of Geriatric Psychiatry and ECT Services and Director of Geriatrics at the Lutheran Medical Center in Brooklyn, New York, and Clinical Associate Professor of Psychiatry at UMDNJ - Stratford, N.J. Dr. Greenberg will discuss the use of ECT in the treatment of agitation associated with dementia. The reported safety and efficacy of ECT in these cases will be reviewed, along with some tentative guidelines and caveats to keep in mind when considering ECT for these patients. Dr. McDonald will discuss the recent data from neuromodulation techniques including TMS, vagal nerve stimulation (VNS), deep brain stimulation (DBS) and transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) and outline the efficacy in geriatric depression. He will offer recommendations for where these treatments should be considered in the treatment of geriatric psychiatric disorders. Specically they will be compared to ECT in terms of the types of patients who would benefit, mechanisms of action and side effect profiles.
