N2  - Background: The long term management of stroke has recently become an area of great interest. The purpose of this study is to review the current evidence surrounding therapeutic interventions for cognitive disorders that have been initiated more than 6 months post stroke, and to determine the strength of evidence to support each intervention. Methods: An electronic literature search of multiple databases was conducted to identify all randomized control trials describing an intervention initiated six months or more post stroke. Levels of evidence were established for each intervention method based on the system established for use by the Stroke Rehabilitation Evidence Based Review (SREBR). Results: A total of 28 studies, including 21 RCT's, were examined. It was found that there is strong evidence to suggest that the use of memantine and compensatory strategies may be beneficial in the treatment of vascular dementia and memory deficits. Conversely, exercise programs may not be effective in treating post-stroke cognitive disorders (strong evidence). There is moderate evidence supporting the use of electroacupuncture, transcranial direct current stimulation, as well as daily aspirin therapy, nimodipine, and donepezil in the treatment of vascular dementia, memory, and cognitive decline. Additionally, computerized training programs have been found to have moderate evidence supporting their effectiveness in the treatment of memory deficits. Conversely, repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation and citicoline have been shown to be ineffective when treating vascular dementia and cognitive disorders. Finally, there is conflicting evidence surrounding the use of anti-hypertensive therapies for the prevention of vascular dementia and cognitive decline more than 6 months post stroke. Conclusions: There is evidence to support the use of several treatments for cognitive disorders post stroke; however, as there are relatively few randomized controlled trials examining these treatments, more research is needed to more fully support the use of many of these interventions.
