N2  - Recent studies have reported enhanced performance on language tasks induced by non-invasive brain stimulation, i.e. repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) or transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS), in patients with aphasia due to stroke or neurodegenerative disease (Alzheimer's Disease - AD, agrammatic variant of primary Progressive Aphasia - avPPA). The aim of the present study was to determine if anodal tDCS (A-tDCS), a method thought to increase cortical excitability, along with individualised speech therapy, would improve naming accuracy in avPPA patients when applied to the scalp overlying the left frontal cortex (BA8/9). Ten patients with early avPPA were recruited, and each patient underwent an extensive language assessment, to identify the items to be treated. A two week randomised intervention was planned, 25 minutes a day, five days a week. During each treatment session real (anodal) or placebo tDCS was applied during 25 min of individualised speech therapy. After two weeks of treatment, a significant improvement in naming was observed in both real and placebo tDCS groups. Interestingly, a significant improvement of Aachen Aphasia test scores was detected only in real tDCS group (10.3%) as compared to placebo tDCS (0%, P=0.021). Our findings suggest a potential role of A-tDCS treatment in combination with speech therapy in avPPA. Longer follow-up will evaluate the beneficial effect of A-tDCS stimulation of left prefrontal cortex in these patients over time.
