N2  - Introduction: There is high level of evidence for DBS for successful symptomatic treatment of movement disorders. Case reports suggest also possible beneficial effects of DBS in HD. Thus, DBS was evaluated in a prospective pilot trial for the symptomatic treatment of HD. Patients and Methods: Six HD patients (2 westphal variants) were examined. Best contact stimulation was chosen after a preceding randomised cross-over period each for 6 weeks of either more internal (GPI) or external (GPE) parts of the pallidum (primary endpoint). After 3 months of best contact stimulation the following outcome parameters were assessed: UHDRS motor score, UHDRS chorea subscore, Burke-Fahn- Marsden-Dystonia-Rating-Scale (BFMDRS), Unified-Parkinson' s-Disease-Rating-Scale (UPDRS-III), cognition (Mattis), depression (Becks-Depression-Inventory, BDI) and Activity of Daily-Living (HD-ADL). Results: UDHRS motor score changed from 55 (SD18) to 49 (SD 24), n.s. excluding westphal patients from analysis, UHDRS change was significant (47 (SD: 16) to 36 (SD: 15), p < 0.01, n = 4). Effects were mainly seen on chorea subscore (9 (SD: 8) to 4 (SD: 3), p < 0.05, n = 6) and 13 (SD: 4) to 5 (SD: 2), p = 0.01, for n = 4 respectively. BFMDRS improved n.s from 28 (SD: 17) to 20 (SD: 27), UPDRS III worsened n.s. (42 (SD: 24) to 45 (SD: 28). BDI, Mattis and HD-ADL showed only minor n.s. changes. Conclusion: This is the first prospective pilot trial reporting positive effects of DBS on chorea in HD. Possible long-term effects on cognition, mood and quality of life will be reported after 12 months follow-up. Distinct motor effects e.g. on dystonia should be addressed in a larger multi-center trial.
