N2  - Background: Bilateral subthalamic nuclei (STN) deep brain stimulation (DBS) in Parkinson's disease (PD) is known to highly improve motor symptoms, to reduce dopaminergic treatments and dopa-linked dyskinesia. It doesn't induce long term psychiatric manifestations or cognitive deficits. Though, many recent studies noticed that social adjustment and psychosocial quality of life (QoL) are not fairly improved after STN DBS. The data highlight “unrealistic” expectations for DBS and its result. Aim/hypothesis: The aim of the study is first to identify, in preoperative PD patients, the “unrealistic” expectations for STN DBS, and second to evaluate the effect of a structured therapy (the Heidelberg's structure formation technique, H-SFT) on social adaptation. We expect that this preoperative structured therapy will have an impact on social adjustment, QoL and development coping strategies. Method: We are focusing on PD patients candidate to bilateral STN DBS. For inclusion and postoperative visits, all patients are investigated for social adjustment, QoL, coping and other psychiatric dimensions. Patients are then randomised in 3 groups: one benefiting of a preoperative structured therapy, the second of a preoperative non-structured therapy, and the third is a control group without specific preoperative intervention. For the intervention group, patients are submitted to a semi-structured interview addressing the personal experience of PD, perceived life before PD and expectations about DBS. Thanks to the H-SFT, we are extracting key words from the retranscripted interview, and reconstructing the structure of the patient's “subjective theories”. Concerning the “cognitive restructuration”, the reconstructed structure of cognitions is presented to the patient in order to reach a consensual dialogue. The “dysfunctional cognitions” are identified and discussed, the examinator trying to balance them, anticipating some behaviour, proposing some alternative actions. Conclusion: This study started in March 2009 and we expect to include about 120 patients for three years. Currently, a mean of 1 patient per month per center have been included. We specifically expect a postoperative improvement of social adjustment, but the specific intervention we are proposing can authorize us expecting more, that is, improvement of not only “physical” but also “psychological” QoL. Maybe also a better comprehension of psychiatric mechanism underlying the deception after successful DBS.
