N2  - Background: High frequency rTMS applied to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (L-DLPFC) has an antidepressant effect based upon adult investigations. There are limited reports of depressed adolescents treated using optimal parameters. The objective of this study was to study feasibility and safety using optimized rTMS treatment parameters in depressed adolescents that had failed at least two adequate antidepressant treatment trials. Methods: This study is a multicenter, prospective, open trial of active rTMS in adolescents with K-SADS confirmed, major depression. Thirty treatments were given five days per week over 6-8 weeks. Ten Hz rTMS was applied to the L-DLPFC at 120% of motor threshold using 3,000 stimulations per session. Participants were monitored throughout treatment and at 6 month follow-up with cognitive, safety and mood instruments. Results: Seven of eight adolescents completed all 30 treatments. No serious adverse events or cognitive deficits were noted during treatment or at 6 month follow-up. Significant mood improvement compared to baseline was noted in CDRS, QIDS and CGI rating scales at 4 weeks, 6 weeks and 6 months Conclusions: rTMS is a safe, feasible and potentially effective antidepressant treatment option in adolescents with treatment resistant depression.
