N2  - Aims: To review recent clinical data with brain stimulation techniques for treatment resistant depression. Background: There has beenmuch interest and several newclinical breakthroughs in using brain stimulation techniques for treating depression, particularly treatment resistant depression (TRD). Methods: Using literature review and knowledge of still unpublished data, this talk critically reviews recent advances in using electroconvulsive therapy (ECT), transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) and vagus nerve stimulation (VNS) for treating depression. All are now US FDA approved for this indication. I will also quickly cover recent and ongoing research studies involving magnetic seizure therapy (MST) and deep brain stimulation (DBS). Results: With ECT, new data demonstrate that shortening the pulse width of the electrical stimulus (ultrabrief pulsewidth) results in more localized seizures that are just as effective as traditional ECT, with markedly less cognitive deficits.1 Moreover, new studies have shown that continuing certain medications while receiving ECT improves the overall remission rate. For example, treatment with nortriptyline enhanced the efficacy and reduced the cognitive adverse effects of ECT relative to placebo. In contrast, venlafaxine resulted in a weaker degree of improvement and tended to worsen cognitive adverse effects.2 With VNS, an open-label study from Europe found response rates that were slightly better than a prior US study. Response rates of VNS as adjunct to stable medications were 53% after 1 year of VNS, and remission rates reached 33%.3 There is still no class I evidence of acute antidepressant efficacy however. With TMS, a recently completed NIH sponsored trial of 190 medication free resistant unipolar depressed patients (OPT-TMS) found that TMS produced significantly more remissions than did sham TMS (15% active, 5% sham). Other new developments suggest that a more anterior and lateral placement of the TMS coil results in more robust antidepressant responses.4 Open series and ongoing clinical trials suggest that MST, or DBS, may also eventually have clinical utility in treating depression, although these techniques are still investigational. Conclusions: The brain stimulation techniques are continuing to evolve and advance and provide new treatment options for patients with treatment resistant depression.
