N2  - Placebo effects are, at least in part, learning phenomena. Therefore, potentially they can be manipulated in a number of ways, with important implications and applications both in clinical practice and in the clinical trial setting. For example, on the basis of the important role of the prefrontal cortex in learned placebo analgesia, it is possible to disrupt the functioning of the prefrontal lobes through pharmacological blockade of opioidergic transmission by means of opioid antagonists. Likewise, the prefrontal cortex can be inactivated by means of transcranial magnetic stimulation, and this causes the loss of the placebo analgesic response. Clinical evidence also indicates that dementia-related functional disconnection of the prefrontal lobes leads to the loss of placebo responsiveness. In addition, it is also possible to use conditioning procedures to create placebo responders and non-responders in the laboratory. All these studies and experimental approaches indicate that placebo responders and non-responders can be created in the laboratory, thus raising important ethical and methodological questions, e.g. whether laboratory-created placebo non-responders can be used in clinical trials.
