N2  - We are conducting a pilot trial of DBS in early PD (IDE G050016). Eligible patients are aged 50-75 and have been on anti-PD medication less than four years. They are without motor fluctuations, dementia, or previous brain operation. We report the perioperative adverse events in 15 patients randomized to receive bilateral subthalamic DBS. Twelve patients (80%) experienced one or more AEs at implantation (range: 1- 12) including headache (4); scalp and/or facial swelling (4); confusion (4); sinus findings identified on planning CT (4); balance difficulty (3); neck pain (2); drowsiness (2); incision site pain (2), swelling (2), erythema (2) or drainage (2); vomiting (2); nausea (2); or difficulty speaking (2). Hematoma, dysphagia, intercranial edema, basal ganglia infarct, sensory changes, extremity weakness, fever, sore throat/swelling, scalp tingling, hallucination, difficulty urinating, constipation and syncope occurred in one patient each. Average duration was 20 days (Range <24 hours-120 days) and none are ongoing. The AE rates described in early PD are similar or better than in patients with advanced PD. A detailed analysis of these safety data is crucial to whether DBS should be made available to patients with early stage PD.
