N2  - Introduction: Stroke and impaired cognition are common, economically costly to society, devastating to patients and their family, and together catastrophic. 30% of people with stroke go on to develop dementia by 5 years. Method: The relationship between cognition (subset of Mini-Mental State Examination, sMMSE, at 90 days assessed by telephone) and baseline demographic and clinical factors was studied in 465 patients (UK/Stroke Research Network-45.2% patients) with acute stroke enrolled into the ongoing 'Efficacy of Nitric Oxide in Stroke' trial. The relationship between sMMSE and other measures of outcome at 90 days was also studied. Results: The sMMSE ranged between 0 and 18/18 (mean 13.35, standard deviation 4.71). In univariate analysis, a low sMMSE at day 90 was associated with increasing age, female sex, previous stroke, atrial fibrillation, haemorrhagic stroke, TACS, low SSS, and high systolic and diastolic BP (all p<0.001); the factors all remained significant in a multiple variable analysis (p<0.001) except a history of previous stroke. There was no relationship with diabetes, temperature or glucose. Lower sMMSE was also associated, in univariate models, with increased dependency (modified Rankin scale, Pearson correlation coefficient, r=-0.368, p<0.001), disability (Barthel Index, r=0.432, p<0.001), quality of life (EuroQOL VAS, r=0.314, p<g0.001) and depression (Zung, r=-0.135, p=0.004) at 90 days. Conclusion: Poor cognitive function at 90 days post stroke is associated with multiple baseline factors, including high systolic and diastolic BP, and with a low functional outcome, quality of life and mood. Lowering BP in the acute phase of stroke is a potential target for reducing poor cognition.
