N2  - Background: Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) might be a new treatment of cognitive deficits in Alzheimer Disease (AD), in combination to traditional drug therapy. By now, there is evidence that TMS treatment could improve naming deficits in AD patients (Cotelli et al., 2006; 2008), but it is unknown if these benefits are long lasting. The aim of this study is to assess the long-term effect of rTMS over the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) in AD patients. Methods: Ten AD patients were recruited at the San Giovanni di Dio Fatebenefratelli Scientific Institute in Brescia, Italy. They were diagnosed as probable AD, based on criteria from the National Institute of Neurological and Communicative Disorders and Stroke Alzheimer's disease and Related Disorders Association (NINCDS-ADRDA). The patients were randomized to two different treatments: i) four weeks of real TMS (Real-Real Group) or ii) two weeks of sham followed by two weeks of real TMS (Sham-Real Group). rTMS was delivered over DLPFC for 25 minutes for each daily session. Efficacy of treatment was assessed at two and four weeks from baseline on the cognitive (language, verbal long-term memory) and functional test scores. Results: Significant difference between groups, for the percentage of correct responses of oral sentence comprehension, was found over sessions (Group x Session interaction: F(1,8)= 6.07, P=.04; r|p2 = .43). Real-Real group improved its performance at 2 weeks (66.6 6 8.6) respect to baseline (77.3 6 6.5, P= .008), whereas in Sham-Real group no significant difference was found between baseline (66.0 6 7.1) and 2 weeks later (65.9, 6 9.6, P= .99). No significant difference was found at 4 weeks between the two groups. Conclusions: Our findings provide evidence of a beneficial effect of rTMS in AD patients. rTMS may be worth testing as a novel approach to the treatment of language dysfunction in AD patients in conjunction with other therapeutic interventions.
