N2  - At present, there is no effective treatment or cure for Huntington's disease (HD) patients. Based on the longlasting successful treatment of other neurodegenerative movement disorders like Parkinson's disease (PD) we evaluated DBS. Questions remained concerning the optimal target. This pilot trial is based on the hypothesis that DBS of the GPI/GPE can reduce choreatic symptoms in HD patients. In addition, this trial should demonstrate which target point within the pallidum can be used effectively for HD in order to further refine this strategy for a multicenter trial. 3 consecutive cases with DBS of the GPi/GPe region are reported. Electrodes and stimulator (Medtronic) were stereotactically implanted under general anaesthesia. No complications occurred. The coordinates for the active contacts in the GPi/GPe range were related to the midcommisural point and individually adapted to anatomical changes. The medication of the patient remained unchanged for the follow-up. Under DBS of the pallidum choreatic movements could be reduced by 50 to 80% (UHDRS). The quality of life, which was measured by ADL, was significantly improved in the three patients. Since the effects were delayed, the adjustment and testing of the remaining contacts took place in the course of several months postoperatively. The most effective active contacts were in projection of the border of GPi and GPe. Systematic positive influence of DBS in Huntington's disease patients is reported for the first time. It will have to be clarified whether the internal or the external part or other targets are suitable for DBS and which long-term results can be obtained.
